Now I found the real issue. Looking at the CSS output:

```css
:root{--sg-selection-bg:var(--primary)}
@supports (color:color-mix(in lab, red, red)){
  :root{--sg-selection-bg:color-mix(in oklch, var(--primary) 12%, transparent)}
}
```

The fallback is `--sg-selection-bg: var(--primary)` which is the primary color (solid, full opacity). When `color-mix` is NOT supported, it uses the full primary color as the background.

In dark mode, the primary color for the dark theme appears to be `oklch(48.8% .243 264.376)` (a dark blue-ish), but in light mode it could be different.


But the screenshot shows the "Fork (steel)" row with a very light or white background, which suggests the dark mode's `--primary` might actually be a light color creating contrast issues. I need to track down what the actual `--primary` value is in the compiled CSS for dark mode, since that's what's being used as the fallback when `color-mix` isn't supported.

The real issue is that my inline style override on the wrapper div should have higher specificity than the `:root` declaration in layout.css, but I'm wondering if the SvGrid component is using scoped CSS variables that redefine `--sg-selection-bg` somewhere else in its own styles, which would bypass my override.

Looking at the screenshot, the selected row has a bright white background in dark mode, which suggests the `--primary` value being used might actually be white or very light. Let me trace through what the dark mode `--primary` is set to in the theme to understand why the selection background is so bright. Let me reconsider what's actually happening here. The inline style override should take precedence over CSS rules, so that's not the issue. But looking at the screenshot more carefully, I'm noticing the white background on the "Fork (steel)" row might not be a row selection at all—it could be a cell-level highlight or focus ring that's being applied across multiple cells. If the grid has cell selection enabled, pressing Space might be triggering a cell range selection rather than a simple row highlight.

My `e.preventDefault()` should be blocking this, but I'm wondering if the grid is capturing the event at a lower level before my window listener fires. Actually, with `capture: true`, my listener should fire first. Let me check the actual compiled HTML to see if the `--sg-selection-bg` override is even being applied, and then look at whether my Space key handler is actually preventing the grid's default behavior.

The real issue is that `e.preventDefault()` only stops browser defaults, not custom JavaScript handlers. If SvGrid has its own keydown listener, it'll still fire unless it checks `e.defaultPrevented`. I could use `e.stopImmediatePropagation()` to block all other handlers, but that might break other keyboard navigation. Since I'm using `window.addEventListener('keydown', onKey, true)` in capture phase, I should be intercepting this first anyway. If I only call `stopPropagation()` for the Space key, it'll prevent just that event from reaching the grid while letting arrow keys and other navigation work fine. So I need to add `stopPropagation()` alongside `preventDefault()` in the keyboard handler for Space. But there's another consideration I'm running into. Adding input guards... I'm tracing through the CSS cascade to understand why the selection background isn't working as expected. The custom property should be overriding from my wrapper div down to the selected rows, but something might be preventing that—possibly an `@` rule or specificity issue that's cutting off the cascade. The solid white background in the screenshot suggests the `@supports` block isn't being applied, so the fallback `--sg-selection-bg: var(--primary)` is taking over—and in dark mode, `--primary` must be white or near-white. I need to check what `--primary` actually resolves to in dark mode within layout.css.

data.content:
reference:  ---
title: Using SvGrid with shadcn-svelte
description: Make SvGrid match your shadcn-svelte design by mapping its --sg-* tokens to shadcn's CSS variables, so the grid blends into the rest of your UI.
date: 2026-06-13
category: Integration
tags: shadcn-svelte, theming, design system, integration, svelte data grid
author: Boyko Markov
---

shadcn-svelte styles everything through a tidy set of CSS variables, `--background`, `--foreground`, `--border`, `--primary`. SvGrid is themed through `--sg-*` variables. Wire one set to the other and the grid stops looking like a guest and starts looking like part of your shadcn UI.

![SvGrid themed to match a design system.](/blog-media/theme-integrations.png)
*SvGrid themed to match a design system.*

## Bridge the tokens

shadcn-svelte defines its palette on `:root` and `.dark`. Map SvGrid's tokens to those same variables:

```css
.app-grid {
  --sg-bg:         hsl(var(--background));
  --sg-fg:         hsl(var(--foreground));
  --sg-border:     hsl(var(--border));
  --sg-header-bg:  hsl(var(--muted));
  --sg-row-alt-bg: hsl(var(--muted) / 0.4);
  --sg-accent:     hsl(var(--primary));
}
```

Because shadcn already defines light and dark values for these variables, the grid gets dark mode for free, flip shadcn's `.dark` class and SvGrid follows.

## Use shadcn components in cells

For custom cells, render shadcn-svelte components inside a snippet so actions match the rest of your app:

```svelte
{#snippet RowActions(p: { row: Row })}
  <Button variant="ghost" size="sm" onclick={() => edit(p.row)}>Edit</Button>
{/snippet}
// column: { id: 'actions', header: '', cell: (c) => renderSnippet(RowActions, { row: c.row.original }) }
```

Keep these accessible, shadcn's `Button` renders a real `<button>`, so keyboard and screen-reader support carry over. See [custom cell renderers](custom-cell-renderers-with-snippets).

## Toolbar consistency

Build the grid's toolbar (search input, filter dropdowns, view toggles) from shadcn components, and let SvGrid own the grid body. The result reads as one cohesive design system.

## Frequently asked questions

### How do I make SvGrid match shadcn-svelte?

Map SvGrid's `--sg-*` variables to shadcn's tokens (for example `--sg-bg: hsl(var(--background))`, `--sg-accent: hsl(var(--primary))`). The grid then inherits shadcn's palette and dark mode automatically.

### Can I use shadcn-svelte components inside grid cells?

Yes. Render them in a Svelte snippet via `renderSnippet`. shadcn components use real interactive elements, so accessibility carries over, and the cells match the rest of your UI.

